The Heraldic Ten were the ceremonial command body of the Void Citadel—ten officers whose
concurrence was required for all major Citadel escalations under the Kel'Shadra institutional
framework. They fused office ritual with military authority, and the Hall of the Ten functioned
as both strategic council and theater of legitimacy. Every major decision required staged
concurrence, allowing each of the Ten to claim constrained responsibility when outcomes were
contested: each officer could truthfully say they were one of ten, that the decision was
collective, that they operated within the framework the others established. This distributed
responsibility was not accidental—it was designed to make individual accountability difficult
to assign. The Heraldic Ten reorganized Citadel enforcement from feudal personal loyalty to
office-based cohort structure, which made rebellion against the institution harder but made
institutional cruelty more impersonal. Their heraldic displays, choreographed oath circles,
and curated military trophies in the Hall of the Ten communicated that legitimacy here was
staged as spectacle. The Ten's concurrence records survive in fragments; they document
escalation decisions but not the deliberations behind them, preserving the appearance of
collective governance while erasing the evidence of individual influence.

